@page "/docs/mcp"
@attribute [Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization.AllowAnonymous]
@using ALDevToolbox.Components.Shared

<PageTitle>Connect an AI assistant · AL Dev Toolbox</PageTitle>

<div class="account-page">
    <header class="page-header">
        <h1>Connect an AI assistant</h1>
        <p class="muted">
            AL Dev Toolbox can be plugged into AI assistants — Claude, Cursor, VS Code
            Copilot, and any other tool that speaks the same protocol. Once connected, you
            can ask the assistant to generate a workspace, look up a procedure on a Business
            Central release, or fetch one of your saved snippets, and it does the work using
            your account here. This page walks through how each assistant connects and what
            it can do once it's in.
        </p>
    </header>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>What's happening under the hood</h2>
        <p>
            AL Dev Toolbox exposes a small set of tools — generate, search, look up — at a
            URL ending in <code>/mcp</code>. Assistants talk to that URL on your behalf.
            "MCP" is just the name of the protocol they use; you don't need to understand
            the details to use it, but you'll see the abbreviation in some assistant
            settings.
        </p>
        <p>
            Whatever the assistant does, it does <strong>as you</strong>: it sees the same
            templates, the same Object Explorer data, the same snippets your browser session
            would. Your role and organisation are unchanged. Nothing the assistant does
            escapes the audit log.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>Two ways to connect</h2>
        <p>
            AL Dev Toolbox supports two sign-in styles for assistants. Which one you pick
            depends on which assistant you're using.
        </p>

        <h3>1. Personal access token (desktop &amp; CLI tools)</h3>
        <p>
            A token is a long, random password you create on
            <a href="/account/access-tokens">your Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a>
            page. You paste it into the assistant's config file or settings, and the
            assistant uses it on every request. Tokens never expire on their own (until you
            pick an expiry date) and don't ask you to sign in repeatedly. Good for:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Claude Desktop</li>
            <li>Cursor</li>
            <li>VS Code Copilot agent mode</li>
            <li>Claude Code (the command-line tool)</li>
            <li>Microsoft 365 Copilot / Copilot Studio</li>
            <li>OpenWebUI</li>
            <li>Anything else that takes an <em>Authorization: Bearer …</em> header</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="muted">
            If a token leaks, revoke it from the same page — the assistant stops working
            immediately. Treat tokens like passwords.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Connect with AL Dev Toolbox (Claude on the web &amp; mobile, ChatGPT)</h3>
        <p>
            Claude's directory and custom-connector flow on
            <a href="https://claude.ai/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">claude.ai</a>, and
            ChatGPT's custom-connector flow on
            <a href="https://chatgpt.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">chatgpt.com</a>,
            can both connect on their own. There's no token to paste — the assistant
            pops up a permission screen, you click <strong>Allow</strong>, and that's
            it. You can take the access back any time from
            <a href="/account/oauth-clients">Account &rarr; Connected assistants</a>.
        </p>
        <p class="muted">
            Under the hood this is OAuth — the same kind of sign-in you'd use to let a
            third-party site read your Google Calendar. You stay signed in for as long as
            the assistant is connected; when you revoke from the Connected assistants page,
            the connection is severed for real (not just hidden). ChatGPT occasionally
            rotates its signing keys — if a refresh happens to land during a rotation,
            ChatGPT will prompt you to reconnect; clicking through gets you back in.
        </p>

        <h3>Which should I use?</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
            <thead>
                <tr><th>Assistant</th><th>Use</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td>Claude on the web (claude.ai)</td><td>Connect with AL Dev Toolbox</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Claude mobile</td><td>Connect with AL Dev Toolbox</td></tr>
                <tr><td>ChatGPT (custom connector)</td><td>Connect with AL Dev Toolbox</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Claude Desktop</td><td>Personal access token</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Claude Code (CLI)</td><td>Personal access token</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Cursor</td><td>Personal access token</td></tr>
                <tr><td>VS Code Copilot agent mode</td><td>Personal access token</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Microsoft 365 Copilot / Copilot Studio</td><td>Personal access token</td></tr>
                <tr><td>OpenWebUI</td><td>Personal access token</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>Step-by-step for each assistant</h2>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>Claude on the web (claude.ai)</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>Open Claude in your browser and go to <strong>Settings &rarr; Connectors</strong>.</li>
                <li>Click <strong>Add custom connector</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                    Paste this URL in the <em>Server URL</em> field — replace <code>YOUR-SERVER</code>
                    with the address of this AL Dev Toolbox deployment:
                    <pre><code>https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>Leave the OAuth Client Secret field empty.</li>
                <li>
                    Claude will pop up a sign-in window. Sign in to AL Dev Toolbox if you
                    aren't already, then click <strong>Allow</strong> on the permission screen.
                </li>
                <li>You're done. Ask Claude to generate a workspace and it'll use the tools.</li>
            </ol>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>Claude mobile (iOS / Android)</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>Open Claude on your phone and go to <strong>Settings &rarr; Connectors</strong>.</li>
                <li>Tap <strong>Add custom connector</strong>.</li>
                <li>Enter <code>https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp</code> as the server URL.</li>
                <li>Sign in and tap <strong>Allow</strong> on the permission screen.</li>
            </ol>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>ChatGPT (custom connector)</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>Open ChatGPT and go to <strong>Settings &rarr; Connectors &rarr; Add custom connector</strong> (or your workspace admin panel's equivalent).</li>
                <li>Enter <code>https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp</code> as the server URL.</li>
                <li>
                    Sign in to AL Dev Toolbox in the popup and click <strong>Allow</strong>
                    on the permission screen.
                </li>
                <li>
                    If ChatGPT later prompts you to reconnect out of the blue, that's
                    typically a signing-key rotation on their side. Clicking through the
                    same flow re-syncs and gets you back in.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>Claude Desktop</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    Create a token on
                    <a href="/account/access-tokens">Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a>.
                    The reveal screen has the snippet below pre-filled with your token.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Open Claude Desktop &rarr; <strong>Settings &rarr; Developer &rarr; Edit Config</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Add the toolbox to the <code>mcpServers</code> block:
<pre><code>{
  "mcpServers": {
    "aldevtoolbox": {
      "type": "http",
      "url": "https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp",
      "headers": {
        "Authorization": "Bearer YOUR-TOKEN"
      }
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>Restart Claude Desktop.</li>
            </ol>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>Claude Code (command line)</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>Create a token on <a href="/account/access-tokens">Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a>.</li>
                <li>
                    From any project directory run:
<pre><code>claude mcp add aldevtoolbox \
  --transport http \
  --url https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp \
  --header "Authorization: Bearer YOUR-TOKEN"</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>The toolbox is available in every Claude Code session in that directory.</li>
            </ol>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>Cursor</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>Create a token on <a href="/account/access-tokens">Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a>.</li>
                <li>Open <strong>Cursor Settings &rarr; MCP &rarr; Add Server</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                    Or edit <code>~/.cursor/mcp.json</code> directly:
<pre><code>{
  "mcpServers": {
    "aldevtoolbox": {
      "url": "https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp",
      "headers": {
        "Authorization": "Bearer YOUR-TOKEN"
      }
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>Cursor reloads MCP servers automatically.</li>
            </ol>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>VS Code (Copilot agent mode)</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>Create a token on <a href="/account/access-tokens">Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a>.</li>
                <li>
                    Add the toolbox to your workspace's <code>.vscode/mcp.json</code>
                    (or your user <code>settings.json</code> under <code>mcp.servers</code>):
<pre><code>{
  "servers": {
    "aldevtoolbox": {
      "type": "http",
      "url": "https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp",
      "headers": {
        "Authorization": "Bearer YOUR-TOKEN"
      }
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>Reload the window. Copilot agent mode picks it up.</li>
            </ol>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>Microsoft 365 Copilot / Copilot Studio</strong></summary>
            <p>
                You author the connection in Copilot Studio; once you publish the agent it
                surfaces in M365 Copilot. The connector runs from Microsoft's cloud, so the
                AL Dev Toolbox deployment has to be reachable over HTTPS from the public
                internet (same constraint as Claude on the web).
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li>Create a token on <a href="/account/access-tokens">Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a>.</li>
                <li>
                    In Copilot Studio, open (or create) an agent and go to
                    <strong>Tools &rarr; Add a tool &rarr; Model Context Protocol</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>Set the <strong>Server URL</strong> to <code>https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp</code>.</li>
                <li>
                    Under <strong>Authentication</strong>, choose <em>API key</em>. Set the
                    header name to <code>Authorization</code> and the value to
                    <code>Bearer YOUR-TOKEN</code>.
                </li>
                <li>Save the tool, then <strong>Publish</strong> the agent.</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                <strong>If the tool list comes back empty</strong> — Copilot Studio builds a
                <em>custom connector</em> behind that tool, and its auto-generated OpenAPI
                definition usually needs two fixes before it can talk to a .NET MCP server.
                Open <strong>Power Apps &rarr; Custom connectors</strong> (in the same
                environment as your agent — this is a different page from <em>Connections</em>,
                which you can't edit), edit the AL Dev Toolbox connector, and switch on the
                <strong>Swagger editor</strong>:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Make sure the operation path is <code>/mcp</code>, not <code>/</code>. The
                    request URL is <code>host</code> + path, so a path of <code>/</code> posts
                    to the app root and never reaches the MCP endpoint — OAuth succeeds but no
                    request ever shows up at <code>/mcp</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Add a <code>produces</code> list with <strong>both</strong>
                    <code>application/json</code> and <code>text/event-stream</code>. The
                    server replies over an event stream, and the connector has to advertise it
                    both <em>accepts</em> one (or the server returns <code>406 Not
                    Acceptable</code>) and knows how to <em>parse</em> one.
                </li>
            </ul>
            <pre><code>paths:
  /mcp:
    post:
      operationId: InvokeServer
      x-ms-agentic-protocol: mcp-streamable-1.0
      produces:
        - application/json
        - text/event-stream
      responses:
        '200':
          description: Immediate Response</code></pre>
            <p class="muted">
                There's no UI toggle for either of these — they live in the Swagger/YAML.
                After saving, update the connector, then reconnect the tool in your agent and
                reload. You should see <code>initialize</code> followed by
                <code>tools/list</code> reach the server.
            </p>
            <p class="muted">
                The agent acts as the user who issued the token — same organisation, same
                role — regardless of which Copilot channel it's surfaced in.
            </p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary><strong>OpenWebUI</strong></summary>
            <ol>
                <li>Create a token on <a href="/account/access-tokens">Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a>.</li>
                <li>
                    Open OpenWebUI's <strong>Admin Panel &rarr; Settings &rarr; Tools &rarr;
                    MCP Servers &rarr; Add server</strong> (or, for a personal connection,
                    your own <strong>Settings &rarr; Tools</strong>).
                </li>
                <li>
                    Add the toolbox with the same shape Claude Desktop uses:
<pre><code>{
  "aldevtoolbox": {
    "type": "http",
    "url": "https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp",
    "headers": {
      "Authorization": "Bearer YOUR-TOKEN"
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Save. OpenWebUI hot-reloads MCP servers — pick a model that supports
                    tool calling, then ask it to use the toolbox.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </details>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>What the assistant can do once it's connected</h2>
        <p>Once connected, you can ask the assistant things like:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Generate a workspace.</strong> "Make me a new workspace from the Acme Customer template, called Acme Pilot v2." The toolbox builds the ZIP and hands it back inline.</li>
            <li><strong>Generate a standalone extension.</strong> "Spin up an empty extension named Sales Bonus, in the Sales prefix, with App Source Cop on." Same flow as the New Extension page in the browser.</li>
            <li><strong>Find a procedure across Business Central.</strong> "In release 28.1, what calls <code>OnAfterValidateNo</code> on the Sales Line table?" The assistant searches Object Explorer and follows references.</li>
            <li><strong>Read part of a codeunit.</strong> "Show me the body of <code>CallPostDocument</code> in <em>Sales-Post</em>." Returns the source, capped at 200 lines.</li>
            <li><strong>Search your snippets.</strong> "Do we have a snippet for opening a side-by-side number range setup?" Fetches matches from your org's library.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="muted">
            The assistant acts as you, with your role and organisation. It cannot generate
            for, search in, or read snippets from another organisation, and it cannot do
            anything a Site Admin can unless your own account is one.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>Available tools</h2>
        <p>
            Each entry below corresponds to a single tool the assistant can call. You
            don't usually need to name them directly — the assistant picks the right one
            for what you asked.
        </p>
        <table class="data-table">
            <thead>
                <tr><th>Tool</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td><code>list_templates</code></td><td>Lists the project templates available in your organisation.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>list_modules</code></td><td>Lists the reusable modules that can be added to a workspace.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>generate_workspace</code></td><td>Builds and returns the ZIP for a new AL workspace from a template.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>generate_extension</code></td><td>Builds and returns the ZIP for a new standalone extension.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>list_releases</code></td><td>Lists the Business Central releases imported into Object Explorer.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>search_objects</code></td><td>Find objects (tables, pages, codeunits, …) by name or id within a release.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>search_procedures</code></td><td>Find procedures by name across a release.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>find_references</code></td><td>Find every place in a release that touches a specific table or field.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>get_object_outline</code></td><td>Returns the symbol list (procedures, triggers, fields) of one object.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>get_procedure_source</code></td><td>Returns the body of one procedure, capped at 200 lines.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>list_procedure_calls</code></td><td>Returns the outgoing calls + field accesses inside one procedure.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>search_snippets</code></td><td>Search the snippet library by name or keyword.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><code>get_snippet</code></td><td>Fetch a single snippet with its file contents.</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>Taking access back</h2>
        <p>
            <strong>If you used Connect with AL Dev Toolbox</strong> — go to
            <a href="/account/oauth-clients">Account &rarr; Connected assistants</a> and
            click <em>Revoke</em>. The assistant is signed out and forced to ask for
            permission again next time.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>If you used a personal access token</strong> — go to
            <a href="/account/access-tokens">Account &rarr; Personal access tokens</a> and
            click <em>Revoke</em> next to the token. The assistant immediately starts
            getting "401 Unauthorized" on every request.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="account-section">
        <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
        <dl class="troubleshoot">
            <dt>"The connector won't add" (Claude.ai)</dt>
            <dd>
                Double-check the URL — it must end in <code>/mcp</code> and be reachable
                over HTTPS from outside your network. If your deployment is behind a VPN,
                Claude's servers won't reach it.
            </dd>
            <dt>"401 Unauthorized"</dt>
            <dd>
                The token is missing, malformed, expired, or revoked. Reissue from
                <a href="/account/access-tokens">Personal access tokens</a>. For the
                connector flow, revoke and reconnect from
                <a href="/account/oauth-clients">Connected assistants</a>.
            </dd>
            <dt>"The assistant says it doesn't see the toolbox"</dt>
            <dd>
                Reload the assistant after adding the connector. Verify the URL by visiting
                <code>https://YOUR-SERVER/mcp</code> in your browser (you'll see a 401 with
                <em>WWW-Authenticate</em> — that's the right response, not an error).
            </dd>
            <dt>"Connector request failed" / no tools load (Copilot Studio)</dt>
            <dd>
                The custom connector behind the MCP tool needs its Swagger fixed: the
                operation path must be <code>/mcp</code> (not <code>/</code>), and its
                <code>produces</code> list must include both <code>application/json</code>
                and <code>text/event-stream</code>. A path of <code>/</code> never reaches
                the MCP endpoint; a missing event-stream type makes the server answer
                <code>406 Not Acceptable</code> before any tool runs. See the Microsoft 365
                Copilot / Copilot Studio section above for the snippet.
            </dd>
            <dt>"Tool calls fail with field validation errors"</dt>
            <dd>
                The toolbox returns the same field-keyed errors the web UI uses. Re-prompt
                the assistant with the missing field or a corrected value.
            </dd>
        </dl>
    </section>

    <p class="muted">
        Still stuck? Ask your Site Admin to check the audit log for OAuth events on your
        account, or reach out internally.
    </p>
</div>
